[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] In mathematics, the **Abel transform**, named for Niels Henrik Abel, is an integral transform often used in the analysis of spherically symmetric or axially symmetric functions.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] In image analysis, the forward Abel transform is used to project an optically thin, axially symmetric emission function onto a plane, and the inverse Abel transform is used to calculate the emission function given a projection (i.e. a scan or a photograph) of that emission function.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] In absorption spectroscopy of cylindrical flames or plumes, the forward Abel transform is the integrated absorbance along a ray with closest distance y from the center of the flame, while the inverse Abel transform gives the local absorption coefficient at a distance r from the center.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] Abel transform is limited to applications with axially symmetric geometries.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] For more general asymmetrical cases, more general-oriented reconstruction algorithms such as algebraic reconstruction technique (ART), maximum likelihood expectation maximization (MLEM), filtered back-projection (FBP) algorithms should be employed.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] In recent years, the inverse Abel transform (and its variants) has become the cornerstone of data analysis in photofragment-ion imaging and photoelectron imaging.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] Among recent most notable extensions of inverse Abel transform are the "onion peeling" and "basis set expansion" (BASEX) methods of photoelectron and photoion image analysis.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] In two dimensions, the Abel transform *F*(*y*) can be interpreted as the projection of a circularly symmetric function *f*(*r*) along a set of parallel lines of sight at a distance y from the origin.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] where *f*(*r*) is the circularly symmetric function represented by the gray color in the figure.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] It is assumed that the observer is actually at *x* = ∞, so that the limits of integration are ±∞, and all lines of sight are parallel to the x axis.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] which yields the Abel transform of *f*(*r*).
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] The Abel transform may be extended to higher dimensions.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] Of particular interest is the extension to three dimensions.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] If we have an axially symmetric function *f*(*ρ*, *z*), where *ρ*2 = *x*2 + *y*2 is the cylindrical radius, then we may want to know the projection of that function onto a plane parallel to the *z* axis.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] which is just the Abel transform of *f*(*ρ*, *z*) in ρ and y.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] A particular type of axial symmetry is spherical symmetry.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] The projection onto, say, the yz plane will then be circularly symmetric and expressible as *F*(*s*), where *s*2 = *y*2 + *z*2.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] which is again, the Abel transform of *f*(*r*) in r and s.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] Consider the case where *F*(*y*) is discontinuous at *y* = *y*Δ, where it abruptly changes its value by a finite amount Δ*F*.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] Such a situation is encountered in tethered polymers (Polymer brush) exhibiting a vertical phase separation, where *F*(*y*) stands for the polymer density profile and $f(r)$ is related to the spatial distribution of terminal, non-tethered monomers of the polymers.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] where δ is the Dirac delta function and *H*(*x*) the Heaviside step function.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] The extended version of the Abel transform for discontinuous F is proven upon applying the Abel transform to shifted, continuous *F*(*y*), and it reduces to the classical Abel transform when Δ*F* = 0.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] If *F*(*y*) has more than a single discontinuity, one has to introduce shifts for any of them to come up with a generalized version of the inverse Abel transform which contains n additional terms, each of them corresponding to one of the n discontinuities.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] The Abel transform is one member of the FHA cycle of integral operators.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] In other words, applying the Abel transform to a one-dimensional function and then applying the Fourier transform to that result is the same as applying the Hankel transform to that function.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] This concept can be extended to higher dimensions.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] Abel transform can be viewed as the Radon transform of an isotropic 2D function *f*(*r*).
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] As *f*(*r*) is isotropic, its Radon transform is the same at different angles of the viewing axis.
[src:hankel-transform/abel-transform] Thus, the Abel transform is a function of the distance along the viewing axis only.
[src:hankel-transform/fourier-bessel-series] In mathematics, **Fourier–Bessel series** is a particular kind of generalized Fourier series (an infinite series expansion on a finite interval) based on Bessel functions.
[src:hankel-transform/fourier-bessel-series] Fourier–Bessel series are used in the solution to partial differential equations, particularly in cylindrical coordinate systems.
[src:hankel-transform/fourier-bessel-series] The Fourier–Bessel series may be thought of as a Fourier expansion in the ρ coordinate of cylindrical coordinates.
[src:hankel-transform/fourier-bessel-series] Just as the Fourier series is defined for a finite interval and has a counterpart, the continuous Fourier transform over an infinite interval, so the Fourier–Bessel series has a counterpart over an infinite interval, namely the Hankel transform.
[src:hankel-transform/fourier-bessel-series] (where: $\delta _{mn}$ is the Kronecker delta).
[src:hankel-transform/fourier-bessel-series] where the plus or minus sign is equally valid.
[src:hankel-transform/fourier-bessel-series] The Fourier–Bessel series expansion employs aperiodic and decaying Bessel functions as the basis.
[src:hankel-transform/fourier-bessel-series] The Fourier–Bessel series expansion has also been used to reduce cross terms in the Wigner–Ville distribution.
[src:hankel-transform/fourier-bessel-series] A second Fourier–Bessel series, also known as *Dini series*, is associated with the Robin boundary condition $bf'(b)+cf(b)=0,$ where c is an arbitrary constant.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] In mathematics, the **Hankel transform** expresses any given function *f*(*r*) as the weighted sum of an infinite number of Bessel functions of the first kind *Jν*(*kr*).
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] The Bessel functions in the sum are all of the same order ν, but differ in a scaling factor *k* along the *r* axis.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] The necessary coefficient *Fν* of each Bessel function in the sum, as a function of the scaling factor *k* constitutes the transformed function.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] The Hankel transform is an integral transform and was first developed by the mathematician Hermann Hankel.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] It is also known as the **Fourier–Bessel transform**.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] Just as the Fourier transform for an infinite interval is related to the Fourier series over a finite interval, so the Hankel transform over an infinite interval is related to the Fourier–Bessel series over a finite interval.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] where $J_{\nu }$ is the Bessel function of the first kind of order $\nu$ with $\nu \geq -1/2$ .
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] which can be readily verified using the orthogonality relationship described below.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] However, like the Fourier transform, the domain can be extended by a density argument to include some functions whose above integral is not finite, for example $f(r)=(1+r)^{-3/2}$ .
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] According to the reference given above, we can take the integral as the limit as the upper limit goes to infinity (an improper integral rather than a Lebesgue integral), and in this way the Hankel transform and its inverse work for all functions in L2(0, ∞).
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] The Hankel transform can be used to transform and solve Laplace's equation expressed in cylindrical coordinates.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] Under the Hankel transform, the Bessel operator becomes a multiplication by $-k^{2}$ .
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] Therefore, the Laplacian in cylindrical coordinates becomes an ordinary differential equation in the transformed function U .
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] is a special case of the Plancherel theorem.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] These theorems can be proven using the orthogonality property.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] The Hankel transform appears when one writes the multidimensional Fourier transform in hyperspherical coordinates, which is the reason why the Hankel transform often appears in physical problems with cylindrical or spherical symmetry.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] Consider a function $f(\mathbf {r} )$ of a ${\textstyle d}$ -dimensional vector **r**.
[src:hankel-transform/hankel-transform] This kind of Hankel transform of half-integer order is also known as the spherical Bessel transform.
