[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] A **Neumann series** is a mathematical series that sums *k*-times repeated applications of an operator T .
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] where $T^{k}$ is the *k*-times repeated application of T ; $T^{0}$ is the identity operator I and $T^{k}:={}T^{k-1}\circ {T}$ for $k>0$ .
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] This is a special case of the generalization of a geometric series of real or complex numbers to a geometric series of operators.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] The series is named after the mathematician Carl Neumann, who used it in 1877 in the context of potential theory.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] The Neumann series is used in functional analysis.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] It is closely connected to the resolvent formalism for studying the spectrum of bounded operators and, applied from the left to a function, it forms the Liouville-Neumann series that formally solves Fredholm integral equations.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] Suppose that T is a bounded linear operator on the normed vector space X .
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] This result on operators is analogous to geometric series in $\mathbb {R}$ .
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] One case in which convergence is guaranteed is when X is a Banach space and $|T|<1$ in the operator norm; another compatible case is that ${\textstyle \sum _{k=0}^{\infty }|T^{k}|}$ converges.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] However, there are also results which give weaker conditions under which the series converges.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] For the Neumann series ${\textstyle \sum _{k=0}^{n}C^{k}}$ to converge to $(I-C)^{-1}$ as n goes to infinity, the spectral norm of C must be smaller than unity.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] This norm is about $0.9056$ as can be checked numerically (e.g., by computing the singular values), confirming that the Neumann series converges.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] A truncated Neumann series can be used for approximate matrix inversion.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] A corollary is that the set of invertible operators between two Banach spaces B and $B'$ is open in the topology induced by the operator norm.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] Indeed, let $S:B\to B'$ be an invertible operator and let $T:B\to B'$ be another operator.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] The Neumann series has been used for linear data detection in massive multiuser multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) wireless systems.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] Using a truncated Neumann series avoids computation of an explicit matrix inverse, which reduces the complexity of linear data detection from cubic to square.
[src:hankel-transform/neumann-series] Another application is the theory of propagation graphs which takes advantage of Neumann series to derive closed form expressions for transfer functions.
